com.apriori.collections

Class FilteringListIterator<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.apriori.collections.FilteringListIterator<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the collection
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Iterator<E>, java.util.ListIterator<E>

    public class FilteringListIterator<E>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.ListIterator<E>
    A filtered view of another list iterator. This is a wrapper that elides all members of the wrapped list iterator that do not match a given predicate.

    Attempts to add/set items in the filtering list iterator that do not match the predicate will throw IllegalArgumentExceptions.

    • Constructor Detail

      • FilteringListIterator

        public FilteringListIterator(java.util.ListIterator<E> iterator,
                             java.util.function.Predicate<? super E> predicate)
        Constructs a new filtering list iterator. Elements in this list iterator will include only the elements from the specified iterator that match the specified predicate. An element e matches the predicate if predicate.apply(e) returns true.

        The wrapped iterator must be initialized to the beginning of the list. In other words a call ListIterator.nextIndex() should return zero.

        Parameters:
        iterator - the wrapped iterator, which should be initialized to the beginning of the list
        predicate - the filtering predicate
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the specified iterator is not initialized to the beginning of the list

      • remove

        public void remove()
        Removes the last item retrieved from the underlying iterable. If neither next() nor previous() has been called then there is no element to remove and an IllegalStateException will be thrown.

        Due to the filtering logic, a call to hasNext() or hasPrevious() may move the underlying iterator (to search for the next or previous element that matches the predicate). In this case, removal is no longer possible and an IllegalStateException will be thrown. So this filtering iterator adds the extra constraint that you cannot interleave a call to hasNext()/hasPrevious() between the calls to next()/previous() and remove().

        Specified by:
        remove in interface java.util.Iterator<E>
